# Gameplay Coding Standards (JS + Three.js)

This project is a browser game in vanilla JS + Three.js (`game.js`, `world3d.js`,
`player3d.js`, `ui-sfx.js`, `site-nav.js`). Apply these engine principles,
translated to this stack.

## Loop & lifecycle
- One `requestAnimationFrame` loop. Use a fixed-timestep accumulator for
  physics/AI; keep rendering frame-rate independent (scale by `dt`).
- Do setup once at module/init time, never per frame.

## Performance first (no expensive calls in the loop)
- NEVER call `document.getElementById`/`querySelector`, `scene.getObjectByName`,
  or `object.traverse` inside the update/render loop. Cache those references once
  at init.
```js
// BAD: lookup every frame
function update() { document.getElementById("hud").textContent = score; }
// GOOD: cache once
const hudEl = document.getElementById("hud");
function update() { hudEl.textContent = score; }
```

## Composition over inheritance
- Keep one module per system, exposing small single-purpose factories/functions.
  Prefer wiring modules together over deep class hierarchies.

## Event-driven input
- Prefer `addEventListener` events over polling state every frame where the
  interaction is discrete (clicks, key press/release, menu actions).

## Memory management (pool, don't allocate in loops)
- Reuse meshes, `Audio`, geometries, and materials; pool recurring objects
  (SFX, enemies, projectiles). Call `dispose()` on teardown/rebuild.
- Don't allocate `new THREE.Vector3()` (or arrays/objects) per frame — reuse
  scratch instances declared at init.

## Code quality
- Group magic numbers into a named "tunable constants" block.
- Use module-scoped `const`/`let` + closures for privacy (JS has no access
  modifiers). Comment only non-obvious math/state, never narrate code.

## Cache busting
- When editing `game.js`, `world3d.js`, `player3d.js`, or `style.css`, bump the
  matching `?v=...` query string in `index.html` (and any page that loads it).
